column1: 98006;instagram;2018-12-28 09:54:10;FALSE;"it's human nature to try and hold on to things.

قبل أن اكون امرأة انا انسان.  نعم انسان  محب و عادل ضد الكراهية  و التمييز الجنسي. ضد التطرف ، انسان محب للاختلاف متقبل لجميع  الاديان  و الاعتقادات  و ذلك أن الله هو الذي  أنزل الاديان جميعا  لتكون  شرائعا للناس و لكن ماذا  فعلوا بها ، استغلوها  ليثبت كل شخص  بأن  دينه  هو الأحق و الله بريء منهم جميعا فالمسلم  موجود و المسيحي واليهودي  موجود  و المثلي  ايضا  موجود  هذا واقع لا يمكن انكاره . انا  ضد اضطهاد المثليين و تجريم  المثلية فليس  بالضرورة  أن يكون  الفرد  مثليا  ليدافع عن المثليين عوض  اظطهاد  المثلي

الذي  لم يرتكب  جريمة  في  حق الإنسانية  و لم يقتل  يوما فل تنظروا الى  الارهابيين  الذين يقتلون  الناس و يقطعون  الرؤوس  البشرية  بإسم  الإله.... انظروا  الى المجرم الحقيقي  ولا تقلوا بعجزكم على الفئات القليله.

";human nature try hold things . قبل أن اكون امرأة انا انسان . نعم انسان محب و عادل ضد الكراهية و التمييز الجنسي . ضد التطرف ، انسان محب للاختلاف متقبل لجميع الاديان و الاعتقادات و ذلك أن الله هو الذي أنزل الاديان جميعا لتكون شرائعا للناس و لكن ماذا فعلوا بها ، استغلوها ليثبت كل شخص بأن دينه هو الأحق و الله بريء منهم جميعا فالمسلم موجود و المسيحي واليهودي موجود و المثلي ايضا موجود هذا واقع لا يمكن انكاره . انا ضد اضطهاد المثليين و تجريم المثلية فليس بالضرورة أن يكون الفرد مثليا ليدافع عن المثليين عوض اظطهاد المثلي الذي لم يرتكب جريمة في حق الإنسانية و لم يقتل يوما فل تنظروا الى الارهابيين الذين يقتلون الناس و يقطعون الرؤوس البشرية بإسم الإله ... . انظروا الى المجرم الحقيقي ولا تقلوا بعجزكم على الفئات القليله . كتابه `` alaksimaa_ قد_الموروث لصلاة لأزهر حمد_شحرور دنان_ابراهيم عد_الدين_الهلالي سلام لحاد اعش يمان جاب لمساواة لمرأة سوية alestine وريا بنان لأردن لسعودية غاني نات غاني راقي لمانية سلام_البحيري لحجاب_عادة_وليس_عباده ;[('human'

column2: everyone noticed. they all stabbed her heart by their cruel words. you see? we all talk about wonder women who are bold
column4: who have done something great for our society but hardly we talk about those women who sacrifice all their dreams just for their family
column5: who make our world little more worth living. heyy! please don't say that they are emotional fool. not every person who love unconditionally is emotional fool. so far
column10: a lawyer etc. but our charm goes away when we say my mother is a 'housewife'. though she plays different roles in our lives. sometimes she is a teacher
column12: sometimes caretaker and everytime a mother. this is my last post for the year 2018 that is purely dedicated to a woman
column14: who don't have degrees and trophies but do have a pure heart
column15: one who doesn't get salary but always do her job selflessly.

column1: p.s: all the things above mentioned are written after some personal experiences.

column1: i started collating information and resources for the women's net website at a time when i was feeling that women were being crushed and were losing our voice:
- gender pay gap reporting was unbelievably disheartening and shows we're still so far off equality in 2018
- trump's ""grab 'em by the x"" comment about how to treat women someone didn't dissuade a whole nation to vote him into power. the mind boggles
column2: and it boggles with disappointment and frustration behind it.

column1: - the #metoo movement crept out from the woodwork to show the far-reaching poison of men who've taken advantage of their 'power'
column2: and who thought they'd get away with it.

column1: i wanted to create a space to boost women up a few notches by making career advice and resources more accessible
column2: and really get into what we can do to achieve that lusted after sense of wellness and balance between work and our personal lives. if we can look after ourselves better
column3: we'll be in a much better position to take on worldwide equality.

column1: @feministabulous: i’ve been thinking a lot about ariana and cardi this weekend and why as women we are often expected to be therapists rather than partners. the absence of a real conversation about men and their mental health
column2: their inability to recognize and treat their pain leaves a void that women are expected to fill and accept. that’s both unfair and sustainable women can’t save the men in their lives if they’re not willing to save themselves first. we can’t heal men’s mental health problems if we don’t even acknowledge they exist. i’ve been trying to get this conversation started and i know many others who are too. it is so overdue.

column1: australian sfx magazine 5 dec 2018: lucy lawless xena in xena warrior princess
at a time when people are celebrating female icons
column2: many are looking back at xena as a groundbreaking show for female empowerment. “the #metoo era is the perfect time to bring back xena and gabrielle to set the world to rights!” says lucy lawless
column3: who played xena from 1995 to 2001 and has starred in battlestar galactica and ash v evil dead. now lawless is about to produce and star in new australian tv drama my life is murder where
column5: “there will be no blood and guts” – for once!

column1: would you like to play the role of xena again?

i would in a one-off. i wouldn’t do the lifestyle again – i couldn’t! that’s for someone young and hungry. i’m always rolling my eyes when there’s an action component in something i’m doing now because i’m so bored with it. but i’d do a limited thing.
what would xena be doing if she was around now?
i like to think she’d be a special prosecutor!
did you keep any set souvenirs?
not so much xena stuff. with xena i think everything was pretty trashed by the end. i might have a few weapons – i’ll let the kids duke it out with them!
what would it say on xena’s gravestone?
i don’t really want to channel arnie
column3: “i’ll be back!” every character i’ve ever played always comes back. “not resting in peace!”

column1: please share something about yourself that might inspire another. here's a portion of my story. .
although i practice spiritually based integrative holistic health enrichment
column2: i had no idea growing up my path would lead me here right where i am at this moment in time. .
so certain gifts i had were frowned upon by society & i began to fear what i now see was a gift. .

column1: i was the teased kid. the abused kid. the odd ball. the artistic kid. the top athlete. i saw ghosts since i was little. the honors student. etc but i never felt like i ever fit in anywhere. i felt like an outcast. there was a hole. .

column2: if i put all the pieces to the puzzle of my life & being a ""signs"" person
column3: i guess i could say there were lots of signs which i really started to pay attention to beginning in 2009. .

column2: i was known as the child dr. doolittle. animals domesticated or wild always somehow found their way to my doorstep in need of human help or intervention from ducks

column1: it was if they had a beacon of ""knowing "" where it was safe to land. .
i was even published in the front page of the patriot ledger when i was 12 attempting to save a seagull that was shot.

column2: i've stopped traffic to help momma with chicks to cross the road to helping a turtle cross a busy road to rescuing a sea hit by a car left on the street w a broken wing to caring for it. .

column1: so i guess the healing path was destined
column2: but growing up i thought being a vet or an illustrator/designer was more practical.

column1: life is precious regardless of what species we are talking about. have you ever stopped to watch ants carry something back home?
fascinating when we can pause a moment to witness simple miracles like that of animals who carry something heavier & larger in great distance in scale no human could ever do. .

column1: 98257;instagram;2018-12-28 05:36:59;FALSE;"this was taken in tulum two weeks before i went to rehab. my face was such a mess 😥 i had already made the decision to go to treatment.

i am a bit odd and went on a two week vacation to mexico for my birthday celebration and used it as my last drinking vacation. i was a highly functional alcoholic that never had any real consequences from my drinking so i took about a month to mentally prepare myself for treatment and have a last resort vacation with unlimited drinks.
however eventhough i had no legal issues or job losses and people told me i was ridiculous for getting help
column2: one of the guys that worked at the resort took me aside and told me he wished i could stop drinking because he was watching me and was worried about me.

column1: it was so sad because i had thought i was not drinking that much and surely no one could tell i had a drinking problem in mexico but he was sober and spotted me easily i imagine. i told him i was heading to treatment in a week and he was so happy for me.

the red spot in the middle of my eyes was from when i was drinking outside alone and dropped a glass of wine and it broke and i fell on it and the glass cut my face. i woke up covered in blood and thankful it didn't cut my eye. it took me six months to get help after that happened.  denial and fear held me back from admitting what was obviously a problem.

column1: i'm giving this letter to you now
column2: when you're eighteen years old and a line of separation has affected our relationship so much. and i know it's not your mistake.
you've lived confined to these four walls. i didn't  let you go to tuitions because while returning it's dark. i didn't let you study in a coed school
column3: because i feared the malicious intentions of guys which may robb me of my most precious stone during the late night school fair.

column1: i didn't give you your deserved freedom to feel your wings
column2: the winds and your abilities. till now
column3: you've lived on my terms. and this affected our bond. and now to you
column4: i'm just your strict father who robbed you of your life

column1: it was when you were one
column2: the little eight year old girl asifa
column3: became the victim of lost humanity in this world.

column1: i was really not that strong like asifa's father
column2: when i saw her smiling photograph i looked back to you. i feared that i may lose you one day.

column1: and i decided to do this.
when i saw tears in your eyes because of me
column2: i wished to melt down but then the unheard screams of pain of asifa used to hit my mind.

column1: when you came to me with a gleam of hope
column2: i wanted to behave like a fighter to make you one
column3: but the fear of losing you for it

column1: i'm sorry for not letting you out in the dark
column2: i'm sorry for making you dress according to my preferences
column3: i'm sorry for robbing your decision making abilities in your life
column4: but it was all for you!

column1: things were really bad that time
column4: the nation failed but all i knew that time was you
column5: your safety! you were the precious part of me
column6: and i wanted to keep it secured in my fraternal environment.

column1: i hope you understand and accept your father
column2: because he is not that bad atleast!
nunnu( this was what i used to call you)

column1: 98291;instagram;2018-12-28 04:20:32;FALSE;"never judge a book by it's cover. some people might seem fine on the outside
column2: but inside they could be struggling. i struggled these past few days with my mother's side of the family. i would like to share a story with you all. i was molested by my uncle when i was 13. i recently had the courage to tell my other family members about what happened and they do not believe me. i do not have proof
column3: but that does not mean that i do not have that memory that changed my life. i am a survivor. my family still invited my uncle to christmas and even had him lead the prayer
column4: which disgusted me to the very core. i want you all to know that you are not alone. there are people that will listen and care for you and they may not be blood. my best friends @princessfirefly and @spikeylovesyndrome helped me through my darkest times and showed me love that i never knew existed. they taught me that i have value and deserve love and respect. please do not think of ever harming yourself. suicide is not the answer. if you feel alone
column5: please call the suicide hotline or 911. they will listen and help.

no more abandoning your resolutions by mid-january!
we all have the best intentions on december 31 of every year. maybe it’s the thrill of starting a brand new year. a clean slate. a fresh start.

column2: many of us will take pen to paper — or fingers to keyboard — and set resolutions for the coming year
column3: some of which will be wildly unreachable. it’s probably because someone once told us that we should aim for the moon — at least if we miss
column4: we’ll land amongst the stars. it’s a lovely saying to hang on the wall or put on a coffee mug
column5: but it doesn’t do ya any favors in the real world.

column2: i wonder how many other girls could begin a letter to you with that opening. here i am saying myrapist
column3: as if i own you. it took me an entire year to allow that word to escape my lips. it was you who owned me. my body that night
column4: and my mind for so long after.do you remember that night? i’ll admit
column5: there was a time i couldn’t recall every little detail. it’s amazing what the human brain is capable of
column6: what it will do to try and retain a smidge of sanity. i spent months attempting to numb myself
column7: to drink away your memory. god
column8: i wanted to forget so badly.

column1: i couldn’t forget though. sure my brain originally spared me the harsh details of your depravity
column2: but you can’t keep secrets from yourself-not for long. the rest of the world however; they could never find out. this was
column4: my fault. wasn’t it? i wonder what you would say if i told you about the night i overdosed on sleeping pills. how i had driven myself mad with self-blame
column5: with racing thoughts and vivid nightmares; that i no longer wanted to live. would you care? would you feel remorse? would you feel anything at all? are you even capable of feeling?

column1: the good thing about a failed suicide attempt (you know
column2: besides the fact that it failed) is that it forces you to make a decision. up or down
column4: live or die. i knew if i was going to remain on this planet
column5: the band aids i had used to cover my scars would need to be ripped open; the wounds cut deeper with every submission to my memory. i would have to see your face
column6: be back in that room. smell the alcohol on your breath and feel your hands on my thighs. first gentle
column7: then forceful as i resisted your touch. i would need to hear the porno playing on the tv in the background
column8: my phone ringing across the room out of reach
column9: your voice. that tone in your voice as you said
column10: “don’t be shy” right before you held me down.that was three years ago.they say time heals all wounds but i disagree; eventually as time passes you just accept them. you stop trying to hide them. you realize living with scars is better than not living at all.

column1: 98307;instagram;2018-12-28 04:40:54;FALSE;"it took me a lot of courage to post this
column2: but there are so many things i want to say after i heard about the irish rape trial
column3: and i refuse to be silent. so here it is.

column1: it’s the same as posting in a bikini.

column3: it’s your wrong to look at it in an erotic way.

column2: underwear with lace is not consent. i don’t understand why it is so hard for people to understand
column3: what the victims(survivors) are wearing is never something we should judge.

column2: i’m very lucky that no one ever asked me what i was wearing after i told my story. but i know there are so many girls and boys out there

column1: the second and third pic is the same outfit i wore the day i got sexually assaulted. what we’re wearing doesn’t matter
column2: how short our skirts or shorts is doesn’t matter
column4: and the only reason is the rapist. .
held up the accuser’s underwear in court and said
column5: ‘does the evidence out-rule the possibility that she was attracted to the defendant and was open to meeting someone and being with someone? you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front.’”

column1: we live in a society where rapist can be a president; we live in a society where a lawyer can held up the accuser’s underwear and said such harmful words that who the hell know how much it’ll hurt the girl.
it’s time to make a difference.
when saying “no” is not a safe and comfortable option
column2: it’s not consent; when we’re wearing something sexy or cute or however you think it looks. it is not consent.

column1: wearing a thong with lace front but saying:
wearing a thong with lace front but:

column3: stop teaching us how not to get raped.
start teaching people the difference between intimacy and assault.

column1: 98312;instagram;2018-12-28 04:47:52;FALSE;"an acronym occurred to me while i was pondering depression recently.  the shitty thing about depression is that it takes your alpha wave state captive and makes basic functions seem really foreign or strange. brains are funny things that are capable of amazing stuff and then forget to drink water.

it's winter and i know a lot of people struggle with cold and dark. i do- in high school i had to get a special lamp to simulate dawn so i could get out of bed every day. we are so intent on spreading cheer because we need to
column2: not just because we want to- i didn't get that until this year. dopamine deprivation is real.

i survived a really big jump off my ex boyfriend's balcony on the 4th floor. obvs it was a dark time... i was struggling regardless but then he essentially kidnapped me and violently tried to rape me. i don't share it a lot but it's not really that hard to tell i have been through shit by looking at me either. i had a lot of these elements going except i guess i stopped learning in my early 20s out of fatalism and heartbreak but if you play then learning becomes enjoyable.

column1: i'm feeling actually pretty good now despite being just out of the ""4th trimester"" and being at a parent's house and being in the suicide capital of the coast. this is my coping mechanism when i start to feel swallowed. it's simplified and excludes a lot of things one could use for levity but it works for me. . reaching out and saying something to someone even can help. get outside yourself

column3: i've come to be extremely proud of myself. i still have sad days but i'm so proud of who i have become despite what life threw at me. .

column1: never give up fighting because time will pass and everything gets easier eventually. so hold on tight and keep fighting through the hard times.  life is about the choices you make and not just what happened to you. .

column2: i did self-harm when i was a teenager because i hurt so much
column3: that physically hurting myself stopped the mental pain for a short time. the thing to realize is that self-harm doesn't change or fix anything and it only temporarily distracts you. if you are going through a difficult time

column5: even to an animal. i've done it and i've also written letters that i've ripped up afterwards. i've even written similar posts to this before and deleted them... all this is to say
column6: keep fighting and working towards self love. never give up on yourself because you are worth more than you realize.♥️ 🦁 .

column1: in a life filled with meaning and accomplishment
column2: michelle obama has emerged as one of the most iconic and compelling women of our era. as first lady of the united states of america—the first african-american to serve in that role—she helped create the most welcoming and inclusive white house in history
column3: while also establishing herself as a powerful advocate for women and girls in the u.s. and around the world
column4: dramatically changing the ways that families pursue healthier and more active lives
column5: and standing with her husband as he led america through some of its most harrowing moments. along the way
column6: she showed us a few dance moves
column8: and raised two down-to-earth daughters under an unforgiving media glare.

column2: a work of deep reflection and mesmerising storytelling
column3: michelle obama invites readers into her world
column4: chronicling the experiences that have shaped her—from her childhood on the south side of chicago to her years as an executive balancing the demands of motherhood and work
column5: to her time spent at the world’s most famous address. with unerring honesty and lively wit
column6: she describes her triumphs and her disappointments
column8: telling her full story as she has lived it—in her own words and on her own terms.

column4: becoming is the deeply personal reckoning of a woman of soul and substance who has steadily defied expectations—and whose story inspires us to do the same.

column1: muitas mulheres são representadas na história como pecadoras e traidoras (eva e maria madalena)
column2: ou como santas (virgem maria). na idade média
column3: o corpo da mulher (quando estava grávida) era visto como morada de deus
column5: quando diziam que elas corrompiam os homens
column6: com sua sensualidade. na transição para o capitalismo
column8: o maior extermínio massivo de mulheres
column9: motivado pelo ódio às mulheres livres

column1: a sexualidade feminina era vista como uma força a ser controlada e reprimida
column2: pois só os desejos sexuais dos homens importavam. que natureza masculina é essa que tanto gosta de assediar
column3: estrupar e matar? que sociedade é essa que tanto odeia mulheres livres e empoderadas?

column1: nossas antepassadas sofreram por séculos essa opressão
column2: porque eram domesticadas e não tinham voz. se uma mulher ousasse amar e se casar com alguém que não fosse escolhido pela família
column3: e se atravesse a estudar e trabalhar

column1: joão dos infernos simboliza a força do patriarcado
column2: homens poderosos que abusam da vulnerabilidade de pessoas
column3: que as manipulam para satisfazer seus desejos.

column4: vemos que é mais complicado o processo da denúncia. o risco de uma mulher ser ameaçada de morte triplica.

column1: é preciso ter coragem. é preciso que uma mulher levante a outra. não podemos mais aceitar a violência de gênero normalizada em nossa sociedade.

column3: não tenham medo de denunciar seus agressores
column4: que não se importem com que a sociedade irá dizer
column5: que estejam protegidas pelo estado e por pessoas queridas
column6: que não sejam questionadas e tenham suas vidas viradas do avesso - para confirmar se são “santas” ou “putas”. minha solidariedade às mulheres que superaram o medo e que tiveram coragem de denunciar.

98426;instagram;2018-12-28 01:45:06;FALSE;hello, survivors- i hope you’re all being kind to yourselves during the holidays. 💚 i’m tempted to check and check and check my insta, and comment and comment and comment on all of your lovely messages, and post and post and post as i’m receiving more submissions and transcribing leaves. but i think it’s for the best that i slow things down a little, and do a little bit of self-care so i can clear my head and ring in the new year with intention. i have a few completed leaf posts that will go up in the next few days, but aside from those, please pardon me if i don’t get back to your dms and emails and kind words until after the new year. but- as always- i see, hear, and believe each and every one of you. i am with you. sending you all love... ✨🌱 column1: we are thrilled to announce rosie šnajdr - we are cosmonauts.

the text will be available as a free pdf & a ltd. edition pamphlet of 21 copies: a collaborative publishing project with @hesterglock_press due jan 2019 ""zero-nine-zero-seven. moscow time. “preliminary stage...” hah. got to… “ intermediate...” huh. got to say. “main…” nuh. jelly spine. numb ass. got to say something. “lift off!” whoof. “have a good flight. everything is a-ok.” the rockets’ rumble rubbing teeth to cinders. is that “a-ok”? need. need some to say something brave. here we go: “poyekhali!” here we go into the history books. the g-force misshaping the smile. brain compacting in base of skull like tushonka. sinking to into helmet. help."" rosie šnajdr is an experimental fiction writer
column2: editor & academic. author of a hypocritical reader (@dostoyevsky_wannabe 2018). her work has appeared in the cambridge literary review
column3: liberating the canon: an anthology of innovative literature (@dostoyevsky_wannabe ) and is forthcoming in the @chicago_review 's #metoo poetry collective

column1: 98686;instagram;2018-12-27 19:34:42;FALSE;"we are thrilled to announce rosie šnajdr - we are cosmonauts.

the text will be available as a free pdf & a ltd. edition pamphlet of 21 copies: a collaborative publishing project with @hesterglock_press due jan 2019 ""zero-nine-zero-seven. moscow time. “preliminary stage...” hah. got to… “ intermediate...” huh. got to say. “main…” nuh. jelly spine. numb ass. got to say something. “lift off!” whoof. “have a good flight. everything is a-ok.” the rockets’ rumble rubbing teeth to cinders. is that “a-ok”? need. need some to say something brave. here we go: “poyekhali!” here we go into the history books. the g-force misshaping the smile. brain compacting in base of skull like tushonka. sinking to into helmet. help."" rosie šnajdr is an experimental fiction writer
column2: editor & academic. author of a hypocritical reader (@dostoyevsky_wannabe 2018). her work has appeared in the cambridge literary review
column3: liberating the canon: an anthology of innovative literature (@dostoyevsky_wannabe ) and is forthcoming in the @chicago_review 's #metoo poetry collective

column1: 98732;instagram;2018-12-27 19:00:41;FALSE;"i am outraged that the violence against women act (vawa) has officially expired due to the partial government shutdown.

since 1994 the vawa has protected victims of domestic violence and sexual assault and was the first federal legislation to recognize and address domestic violence as a serious crime. domestic violence and sexual assault programs funded by vawa will be cut off until the legislation is reauthorized.

column3: i am utterly disappointed. you'll be hearing more from me on this topic. i'll never stop fighting for what's right.

column2: and many more (i’m one of 5 women in a department of 200 men) joined in. so i raised my voice and said i was glad women were speaking up about sexual harassment and assault and that i hoped that everyone who perpetuated this toxic behavior got taken down. “yeah but it’s a trend now
column3: lots of them are just saying it for their 15 minutes of fame.” he then continued to say that he didn’t know anyone who had been harassed or any man who had done it. i asked him if he had a daughter. he did. i asked him how old she was. she was was 17. i told him i’d bet my rent money that his daughter had experienced sexual harassment. “that’s impossible.” “did you ask her?” “no.” “well then
column5: he came in the office with five bouquets of flowers for all the women in our department
column6: including me. he publicly apologized for making fun of sexual harassment and for making our lives harder by doing so. he said that he simply hadn’t known how widespread it was. apparently
column7: his daughter deals with it very regularly. she hadn’t told him because of the way he spoke about assault cases that were on the news. she thought he’d think less of her if she’d mention it. it was her idea that he should make a public announcement. he said he felt like a bad father.

column1: i said: “you were. same goes for everyone who laughed with you. be better
column2: now you know better. and educate other men that still think the same way you did yesterday. and next time someone tells you about an experience they have
column3: don’t automatically assume that because you haven’t seen it
column4: it’s not true. that kind of willful ignorance is why we still deal with this shit.” he also offered to pay my rent as that was part of the bet
column5: but i told him i’d rather have him put effort in being a person his daughter and wife could be proud of.” see comments for continued id.] [tags: #feminism#feminist]";;en;#metoo

column1: dopo l'ultimo video di #kevinspacey credo sia arrivato il momento di parlare del mio problema con il #movimentometoo.

se sono d'accordissimo e felicissimo che qualcosa stia cambiando e della serie infinita di denunce che ci sono state e che hanno puntato il dito verso determinate persone e determinati comportamenti io credo che ci sia un problema generale con l'#after denuncia.

se infatti non ho problemi con una donna o un uomo che denuncia un abuso non sono minimamente d'accordo con la messa al bando istantanea della persona denunciata senza che vengano prima fatte delle opportune indagini.

allo stesso tempo se la persona in questione non viene condannata in nessun modo si deve trovare un modo per riportarlo sullo schermo o sul palcoscenico mettendo fine al suo calvario perchè magari non ha fatto nulla e si è sempre innocenti sino a prova contraria.
capisco tutto ma non posso credere per partito preso ad una denuncia perchè non è giusto.
si deve trovare un modo per rimettere al loro posto chi ne è uscito indenne.

column1: 98890;instagram;2018-12-27 15:54:04;FALSE;"the solo ride to spiti in october was one of my most memorable trips this year. riding in freezing temperatures with snow laden peaks all around is a challenging yet beautiful experience. exploring spiti all on your own with your bike is a test of both your physical and mental strength.

this pic was clicked at komic - a village near kaza claimed to be the highest village in the world with a motorable road and the site of the world's highest homestay. i still remember stopping my bike every 5-7 minutes while approaching this village to rub my palms and make sure that my hands don't fall numb in the cold. but like the wise men say - harder the effort

column3: es que es una feminista pura crecida y nacida en nigeria. ella aprendió sobre el feminismo a través de vivencias personales y fue capaz de reconocer las injusticias sociales en las que vivía. la semana pasada leí su libro llamado “dear ijeawele

98961;instagram;2018-12-27 14:05:19;FALSE;"det skrämmer mig verkligen när jag ser (framförallt 🙄) snubbar skriva att dom känner sig rädda efter #metoo. varför? ser liksom ingen anledning till att vara ""rädd"" om man inte själv gjort sig skyldig till ett övergrepp. ännu mer skrämmer det mig hur arga en del verkar vara efteråt - inte på att folk som jag
column2: din syster och din mamma löper stor risk att bli utsatta
column3: utan snarare över ""generaliseringen"" över vilka det är som begår övergrepp. om ens första impuls när någon berättar om ett övergrepp är att bli arg eller att försvara sig själv (""jag skulle aldrig göra nåt sånt"") så verkar det lite... skumt
column4: på nåt sätt. om du inte har gjort något
column5: varför ser du då ett så starkt behov av att hävda sin oskuld om ingen anklagat dig? i flera fall ser jag hur ilskan riktas åt helt fel håll. istället för att bli arg och vilja förändra att övergrepp sker
column6: så blir vissa arga på att övergreppen blivit synliggjorda av de utsatta - samtidigt som de hävdar att de är helt oskyldiga men nu blir utsatta för en generalisering. inte så logiskt
column7: alla vet ju att det inte är alla män som våldtar så ser inte poängen med att påpeka det så fort någon berättar att den har blivit utsatt. kan även påpeka att jag ser det här beteendet från alla politiska håll och bland flera individer och av olika anledningar
column8: beroende på vems politiska ideologi förövaren skulle kunna gynna bland annat. skärp till er. ser folk som berättar att de blivit tafsade på av invandrare bli tystade för att ""sd kommer gynnas av det här""
column9: ser folk som berättar att samma sak har hänt av en helsvensk som inte tas på allvar för att ""majoriteten av de som våldtar är invandrare"". sluta säga att ni bryr er om ni bara gör det när det gynnar er
column10: vi ska stötta de utsatta och inte gärningsmännen.

column1: 98974;instagram;2018-12-27 14:19:11;FALSE;"maybe you can’t see much difference here but i can.
this is a different kind of before and after.
these pictures were taken a year to the minute apart. even taken in the same spot.
the one on the left though
column2: was a hell of a lot more sober than the one on the right.

column1: i almost made it a year before i convinced myself that “hey! i’m pretty good at controlling myself
column2: i should have a drink every now and then”. and for a while
column3: that’s what it was. then one after another things in my already overwhelming life began falling apart.

column1: drinking allowed me to make some of the worst mistakes in my life this last year. mistakes i may never fully recover from.

column2: i haven’t hit rock bottom. no
column3: my liver isn’t about to die (that i know of)
column4: but this is not how i want to live. i want a clear head at night before sleeping and to wake up without the feeling of guilt from something i said or did the night before.

column1: as a complete fool once said to me
this before picture is a motivation for me.

column2: i don’t want to go back. and no

column1: it’s about the person that was hiding from everything in both pictures.
alcohol only numbs a pain that will return until it has been fully felt.
i’m not afraid. i have hope.
i’m taking my life back one day at a time.
fuck alcohol and fuck drunk natalie and fuck the idea that alcohol makes everything more fun.
you won’t hear me say “i’m an alcoholic”. because i’m not.
i’m an adventurer who lost her way.
i’m thankful to @thisnakedmind for the encouragement and permission to live authentically.
